<HEADLINE> Iraq Refutes U.S. Claim on No-fly Zones Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Saturday refuted the U.S
claim that the U.S.-British warplanes have carried out raids
against Iraqi targets in the no-fly zones in response to Iraqi
provocations, calling them "sheer lies."
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency, Iraqi Air
Defense Commander Shaheen Yassin Mohammed said the claimed 108 air
raids by U.S.-British warplanes against Iraqi targets since last
December were not for monitoring the no-fly zones but for
aggression against Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
He added that the aggression is an obvious violation of the
international legitimacy, the U.N. Charter and relevant Security
Council resolutions which state that Iraq's political
independence and territorial integrity must be respected.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed said that no international resolution or law provides
for the imposition of no-fly zones in Iraq, adding that the
restricted zones were imposed unilaterally by the U.S. and Britain
to prevent Iraqi planes from flying in its southern and northern
airspace.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S. and
Britain following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in
the south against any possible attacks by Iraqi government
troops.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the actual number of sorties made by
U.S.-British warplanes coming from Saudi, Kuwaiti and Turkish
bases over the two no-fly zones since last December has reached
10,977.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian and
military targets in the no-fly zones, causing severe civilian
casualties and property damages.
</P>
<P>
The general said that the U.S. has compressed the number
to less than one percent in an attempt to lessen the dangers
of those raids and to avert the world's attention from the
brutal crimes committed against civilians, civil facilities and
residential areas.
</P>
<P>
He said that 138 civilian and military sites have been targeted
by the enemy planes since last December, and civilian facilities
were targetted intentionally and not mistakenly.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that Iraqi air defences have the full right
to fire back at the enemy planes that violate Iraqi airspace
because they are defending Iraq's sovereignty and territorial
integrity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
