<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Forces, Caucasus Gunmen Exchange Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian helicopter gunships
launched missile attacks Saturday on positions held by armed men
around a village in Russia's troubled North Caucasus region of
Daghestan, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian ground forces were also exchanging fire with the armed
infiltrators -- several hundred men who surrounded two or three
villages after crossing into the remote mountainous region from
the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of casualties on either side.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Saturday, Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin ordered
Defense and Interior Ministry forces to "normalize the situation"
swiftly.
</P>
<P>
"Bandits are bandits," he said in televised comments during a
visit to the Volga city of Ulyanovsk.
</P>
<P>
"One needs to tackle them appropriately. We have the forces and
means," Stepashin said. "I don't see any other way."
</P>
<P>
"Russia will not repeat its mistakes in the North Caucasus," he
stressed. "No more Russian soldiers will die there."
</P>
<P>
Russia has taken an increasingly robust stance on the rising
number of incidents on its troubled southern flank, using
helicopter gunships to launch preventive strikes against suspected
guerrilla bases inside Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Daghestan and the entire northern Caucasus region have remained
in turmoil despite the August 1996 ceasefire that ended the
Chechen conflict.
</P>
<P>
Neighboring republics have seen a wave of hostage-taking from
crime gangs based in Chechnya, and chronic poverty has compounded
the inherent political instability in republics like Daghestan,
which has a fragile mix of more than 30 separate ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
According to the Russian Interior Ministry, 1,094 people have
been abducted since January 1, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
