<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian FM Writes to UN Chief on Conflicts With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi on Saturday wrote to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan,
urging the world community to pressure Afghanistan's Taliban
to abide by international laws, regulations and norms.
</P>
<P>
The letter was delivered on the eve of the first anniversary of
the killing of Iranian diplomats and reporter by Taliban militants
when they took over Mazar-i-Sharif, a stronghold of the opposition
forces in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
On August 8, 1998, eight Iranian diplomats and a reporter of
the official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) were captured and
eventually slain after Taliban troops seized the Iranian consulate
in the city.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been a supporter of the opposition forces against the
Taliban, the religious students' movement that has the backing of
Pakistan and has taken control of most of the country in the civil
war.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Kharrazi said he wants to draw Annan's attention
"to the disrespect for the international law by the
Taliban ... and their inhuman activities," the IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Infuriated by the killings, Tehran massed nearly 200,000 troops
along its border with Afghanistan to press for the return of the
bodies of the victims, an apology, identification and punishment
of the killers.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said the United Nations Security Council resolutions
provided necessary political and legal grounds for identifying and
bringing to trial those responsible for the crime.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan's six neighbors - Iran, Pakistan, China,
Tajikistan, Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan - and Russia and the
United States, commonly known as the "six plus two" group in this
respect, have been trying to help bring the conflicts to a
peaceful end.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said the decisions made by "six plus two" in both
their New York meeting last year and Tashkent (Uzbekistan)
meeting in July stressed that the Taliban should be obliged to
heed the desires of the international community to identify, try
and punish those responsible.
</P>
<P>
But he said that so far the pleas and efforts in this regard
"have fallen on deaf ears." He asked the U.N. chief to do more
over this issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
