<HEADLINE> Russian PM Honors Kosovo Airport Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin on
Saturday gave awards to Russian soldiers who made a surprise dash
to the Pristina airport in Kosovo ahead of NATO forces on June 12.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, in the central Russian city of Ulyanovsk, told
members of the 31st Brigade of airborne troops that they were
being honored for fulfilling their duty and displaying courage and
heroism, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The troops are based in Ulyanovsk, 500 miles east of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin said that while the brigade had suffered losses
during its history, it had suffered "no loss of honor, conscience
and dignity."
</P>
<P>
On June 12, about 200 Russian paratroopers surprised NATO
officials by making a lightning dash from Bosnia, where they had
been stationed as peacekeeping troops, to Pristina, where they
took over the Slatina airport.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that Russian President Boris Yeltsin himself
had given the orders to send the troops to Pristina, a move that
prompted a standoff between Russia and NATO.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was later worked out between U.S., Finnish and
Russian officials that provided a blueprint for Russian
participation in peacekeeping operations in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
Russia has nearly completed its deployment of some 3,600 troops
in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
