<HEADLINE> 2 Killed in Quarrels Over Soccer Matches in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Two men were killed in Cairo, the
capital of Egypt, on Saturday in two quarrels over football
matches.
</P>
<P>
The first incident took place in a youth club in Zamalek
district in Cairo. When a goal was scored against his soccer team,
Fatin Hamza contested the validity of the goal with the referee,
Hassan Khaled Hassan.
</P>
<P>
The two men argued, and Hassan, a video store owner, lost his
temper and repeatedly stabbed in the chest of Hamza, an official
said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
In the second match, played in a Cairo working class district,
an argument broke out when Mohammed Saleh Abdel-Samei, who was
walking by the pitch, was struck by a wild shot Wael Abdullah
Hamouda has taken on the goal.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Samei stabbed Hamouda in the chest, witnesses said.
</P>
</TEXT>
