<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nightmare Still Haunting Kenyans One Year After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIRIBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A year after the horrible bombing
of the U. S. embassy in the Kenyan capital Nairobi, people are
still haunted by the nightmare and struggling to come to terms
with the cruel reality.
</P>
<P>
"Why choose Kenya? What is Kenya guilty of?" Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi asked in his speech at the rally to commemorate
the first anniversary of the blast, which indiscriminately killed
254, mostly Kenyans, and injured more than 5,000.
</P>
<P>
"The perpetrators of this ugly attack intended to massacre
their perceived enemies," Moi told the gathering of diplomatic
corps, Kenyan and American victims and other people.
</P>
<P>
"The aftermath of the bomb blast was a trail of blood, death,
and the tears of crippled and blind people and numerous orphans
born in freedom but who had to see their parents perish at the
hands of international terrorism," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people on the site of the battered former U.S.
embassy, which is designed to be converted into a memorial park,
listened to the speech in silence. Victims of the blast and
diplomats wore white and violet ribbons on their chest, which
symbolizes peace and unity.
</P>
<P>
Prayers by clergymen of Christianity, Hinduism, Muslim, Jewish
faith called for peace, healing, courage and forgiveness. A minute
of silence was observed to show respect for the dead. Wreaths were
laid before a red podium. Candles were lit. Solemn music echoed
around the tragic bombing site.
</P>
<P>
After the rally the people who lost their beloved hugged each
other and cried as they recalled the dark moment.
</P>
<P>
A woman cried out and her two children, a three-year-old and a
five-year- old wept along with her.
</P>
<P>
One middle-aged man who clutched a framed picture of a woman
told Xinhua that his wife died in the blast. He choked and eyes
became wet.
</P>
<P>
Michael Marine, Charge d'Affaires of the U.S. embassy in
Nairobi, said in his speech that the bonds between the United
States and Kenya and the two peoples were "stronger than ever".
</P>
<P>
However, Japheth Maingi, a survivor of the bombing, told Xinhua
that one year after the blast his family has not got any
compensation from the U. S. government.
</P>
<P>
"Not a single shilling," he said. "I have paid 10,000 shillings
( about 156 U.S. dollars)  for medical fees to treat the bone
fracture in my knee."
</P>
<P>
Maingi also told Xinhua that his brother Robert died in the
terrorist explosion, when he was working on the seventh floor of
the Co-operative House.
</P>
<P>
The blast destroyed millions of dollars worth of property and
killed many bread-winners in a relatively poor country, dealing a
heavy blow to the country's already flagging economy.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan major newspaper Daily Nation carried an article on
August 6, saying that some Kenyans affected by the bombing
believe that the compensation offered by the U.S. government may
not be beyond mere symbolism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
