<HEADLINE> Sudan Hopes for Initiative to End Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister
Mustafa Ismail Osman expressed his country's hope here on Saturday
that a single proposal could be worked out through coordination to
end the civil war in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing, Osman expressed appreciation of
the proposals separately submitted by Egypt, Libya and the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD) on ending the
civil war in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed the hope that these proposals could be
merged into a single one.
</P>
<P>
He said the Sudanese government is expecting the Libyan envoy
in Khartoum to inform the Libyan leadership of Sudan's
appreciation of the Libyan proposal which calls for securing
proper climate for productive talks between the government and the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Libya suggested early this month that the rival parties in
Sudan negotiate to find a peaceful solution to their disputes. It
also calls for cease-fire and setting up a preparatory committee
to work on the proposed negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Osman denied Western reports that the Sudanese government used
chemical weapons against the rebel Sudanese People's Liberation
Army led by John Garang.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister renewed his country's call for the
establishment of a neutral body to investigate into such claims.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have been waging a war to seek autonomy for the
country's south, which is largely populated by Christians,
from the Muslim-dominated central government.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.9 million people have been killed in the war since
it started in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Khartoum also called on the United Nations to send a
fact-finding mission to Sudan to conduct an investigation of a
chemical factory in Khartoum, which was destroyed in an air
bombing in August 1998 by the United States under the claim that
it was a chemical weapon factory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
