<HEADLINE> Zambia's Mediation Delayed by Congo War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Mediation to end conflict in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has been delayed as rival
rebel factions in the country fought a gun battle at the rebel
stronghold of Kisangani Saturday, preventing a Zambian peace
delegation from flying into the jungle city.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said soldiers loyal to rebel leader
Ernest Wamba dia Wamba battled troops loyal to rebel Emile Ilunga
at an airport in the northeastern city on the Congo River.
</P>
<P>
The fighting lasted around 10 minutes before Ilunga's troops
were arrested and there were no reports of casualties.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the battle, Zambian Minister of State House Eric
Silwamba delayed his arrival in the city, according to rebel
troops.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba arrived in DRC this week in an attempt to persuade the
divided rebel Congolese Rally for Democracy (CRD) to sign up to a
peace agreement signed in Zambian capital Lusaka last month.
</P>
<P>
The deal aims to end a year-long conflict in the DRC. All the
governments involved in the conflict signed the cease-fire
document.
</P>
<P>
But the CRD, which now holds much of the eastern half of the
country, refused to sign because of a leadership struggle between
Dia Wamba and Ilunga, who in May ousted Dia Wamba as the group's
official head.
</P>
<P>
Ilunga's troops are based in Goma on the Rwandan border, while
Dia Wamba is based in Kisangani, a Ugandan stronghold.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian mission has shuttled between the two locations, as
well as visiting the Rwanda and Uganda capitals.
</P>
<P>
However, leader of the Movement for the Liberation for Congo
(MLC), Jean- Pierre Bemba has signed the cease-fire agreement in
Lusaka last Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
