<HEADLINE> Iran's Cheetahs on Verge of Extinction: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Cheetahs are on the brink of
extinction in Iran mainly due to environmental degradation,
lack of access to food, and poaching, a major Iranian ecologist
said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Asgar Mohammadi-Fazel, the head for co-ordinating a national
strategy on ecological diversity, sounded the warning at a
gathering of directors of provincial environmental protection
departments.
</P>
<P>
"Mis-guided cultural beliefs in the carnivorous nature of the
animal has led to a hunting spree in Asia and other parts of the
world," he said while specifying the poaching factor in the
reduction of the rare animal.
</P>
<P>
Cheetah, the world's fastest land animal, has been observed
running at a velocity of more than 105 kilometers per hour while
in pursuit of prey.
</P>
<P>
Being at the head of the ecological pyramid, cheetah's presence
in any region is effective for the health of the environment,
Mohammadi-Fazel said, quoted by the official Islamic Republic News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
With the cooperation of the United Nations and several other
organizations, he said, important projects are being carried out
to ensure that the rare animal might have a chance to survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
