<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Starts to Build New Embassy in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States Friday
started to build a new embassy in Tanzania one year after the twin
bombings in east Africa.
</P>
<P>
A ground-breaking ceremony for the construction of the new
embassy was held in an open space in north Dar es Salaam, where
U.S. ambassador Rev. Charles Stith used a shovel to turn dirt.
</P>
<P>
Wearing a construction helmet, Stith said the ceremony marks a
new chapter in the history of U.S. presence in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"The new United States Embassy that will go up this site will
be a testament to our tenacity in the face of terrorism...and a
symbol of our commitment to our relationship with the people of
Tanzania," Stith said.
</P>
<P>
Stith was accompanied by Deputy Assistant Secretary of State
for the Office of Foreign Buildings, Patsy Thomasson, and
Permanent Secretary in Tanzania's Ministry of Foreign Affairs and
International Co-operation, Elly Mtango.
</P>
<P>
Thomasson told Xinhua Saturday that construction of the new
embassy, an edifice, will take three years with a cost close to 50
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a sculpture "Hope out of Sorrow" was unveiled at the
National Assembly to mark the first anniversary of the bombing of
U.S. embassy in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Twelve people were killed and more than 70 others injured in
the terrorist bombing here on August 7, 1998. A simultaneous
attack on U.S. embassy in Nairobi, Kenya killed more than 200
people and 5,000 others.
</P>
<P>
The sculpture, an armless woman made of clay and cement, was
designed by Swedish artist Clara Sornas, who is also the curator
of the Zanzibar Slave Memorial Museum.
</P>
<P>
The sculpture stands in front of a fractured glass screen taken
from the bombed U.S. embassy site. Surrounding the piece of work
are several wrecked bicycles, motorcycles and other items taken
from the same place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Reserve Bank Not to Undergo Great </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Former Labor Minister Tito
Mboweni, who will become South African Reserve Bank (SARB)
governor, said Saturday that there will be "no earth-shattering
changes" at the bank.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni was addressing the media in Johannesburg only hours
before his inauguration as the supreme of South Africa's premier
financial institution. He takes over the rein from Chris Stals
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said that while there could be currency speculation with the
 changeover of the SARB governorship, he was not over-concerned
about speculators.
</P>
<P>
"There is a market place out there and people are entitled to
do certain things. But sometimes you win, and sometimes you lose.
I don't want to see people withdraw money from the bank on
Tuesday. I want them to deposit it and get interest. I also want
to see money coming into the country."
</P>
<P>
Mboweni said he now wanted to focus on his immediate
responsibility at the SARB and do all he could to ensure a stable
financial environment in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The governor-designate outlined policies on several monetary
issues.
</P>
<P>
Inflation targeting, understood to be favored by Finance
Minister Trevor Manuel and cabinet colleagues, would have to be
"core managed", he said, adding that it was not cut and dried as
it could impact on wages and trade.
</P>
<P>
Exchange rate targeting, he said, had been "discredited, and
was a waste of time".
</P>
<P>
Mboweni said he was also in favor of "integrated regulation" of
 financial institutions as he noted that banks and insurance
companies were now offering far more additional services.
</P>
<P>
Artificially low interest rates were however out, as "the cost
has to be paid for down the line," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni will be having talks Monday with various representative
of African and overseas Central Banks, who with President Thabo
Mbeki, were attending his inauguration banquet Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Among the topics to be discussed will be the plight of the
heavily indebted poor countries, the role of banks in emerging
markets, and the reduction of volatility in capital markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
