<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sockeye Fishery Closed in British Columbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Canadian western province of
British Columbia has closed sockeye fishery along Fraser River due
to a drastic shortfall in returning fish.
</P>
<P>
The move, which means losses of millions of dollars, is dealing
another blow at British Columbia's troubled salmon industry, media
reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The closure came after the country's Pacific Salmon Commission
recommended action Friday, with sockeye returns expected at 40
percent of usual predictions.
</P>
<P>
Only three million sockeye will return to the river to spawn
this year, compared with earlier estimates of 8.2 million,
according to Wayne Saito, chairman of the commission's Fraser
River panel.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall is linked to the after-effect of the El Nino
phenominon. Higher ocean water temperature, decreased food
supplies and the move northward of predatory fish have harmed the
development of this year's sockeye runs, reports said.
</P>
<P>
This is not the first time the Fraser sockeye fishery has been
closed. In 1995, local authorities decided to curtail the fish run
when only four million sockeye returned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
