<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Joins 22 Countries in Ratifying Fish Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Canada has joined other 22
countries in ratifying the United Nations Fish Agreement, known as
UNFA, the local media said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy was quoted as
announcing Friday the ratification of the framework for
international cooperation on fisheries management on the high
seas.
</P>
<P>
The agreement comes into force 30 days after as many as 30
countries ratify the deal, the media said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for international cooperation for the
conservation and management of fish stocks that straddle
international boundaries in heavy migration, according to the
local media.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also contains a compulsory binding dispute
settlement mechanism, the report said, indicating that Canada, in
case of any conflict, may have to include its straddling stocks of
cod, flounder, red fish, turbot, swordfish and tuna in negotiating
a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Russia, Iceland and Norway are among the
countries which have ratified the UNFA, the media said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
