<HEADLINE> Violence Flares as Football Season Kicks off in Cardiff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON August 7 (Xinhua) The center of Cardiff, Wales has been
cordoned off Saturday afternoon amid clashes between hundreds of
rival football supporters, according to BBC report.
</P>
<P>
Police wearing riot gear moved in as Millwall fans arriving for
their team's match with Cardiff City charged through the streets,
throwing missiles.
</P>
<P>
Around 600 Millwall fans are thought to have arrived in the
city to see their team take on Division Two newcomers Cardiff. Two
people have been arrested following clashes between the fans.
</P>
<P>
Police are keeping rival gangs of supporters separated as they
escort Millwall fans from Cardiff Center railway station to the
Ninian Park ground for the match.
</P>
<P>
The trouble comes days after a report by the National Criminal
Intelligence Service found violence was escalating among football
fans.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for South Wales Police said no one had been
injured during skirmishes in the St Mary Street area of the city.
She said there were no reports of damage to shops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
