<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Compensates Nazi Victims During World War 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON August 7 (Xinhua) Britain has agreed to the first
compensation payments to Nazi victims who had assets seized during
the second world war, officials announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The British government confiscated bank accounts and valuables
from citizens of countries allied with Nazi Germany during the
war. The scheme was designed to prevent money going back to
Germany to finance the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
Among assets taken were millions of pounds belonging to Jews
and other victims of the Holocaust across Europe during the war.
</P>
<P>
More than 130,000 pounds will be paid out to 10 claimants under
a scheme which was launched last December to compensate those
whose possessions and money were confiscated as "enemy property"
under the trading with the enemy act 1939.
</P>
<P>
A worldwide search is now under way to find more people who
tried to escape Nazi persecution, and had property confiscated by
the British authorities.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the first payments, Trade and Industry Secretary
Stephen Byers urged other victims to come forward. Only 250 claims
have been made since details of 30,000 pieces of property were put
on the internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
