<HEADLINE> Mideast Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RYIADH -- Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Bin Abdul Aziz
issued a decree Saturday earmarking 20 million U.S. dollars to
purchase 21,000 tons of local dates this season, Agriculture and
Water Minister Abdullah Bin Abdul-Aziz Bin Muammer told the Saudi
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Most of these dates would be distributed among the local poor
people and the remaining amount would be given to the impoverished
areas around the world through the World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian stock exchange witnesses rise of some indices
over the first six months of this year. Market capital of listed
companies surged to 93.7 billion pounds (27.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The number of the listed companies rose from 861 in December to
960 by the end of June, the Egyptian daily Al Ahram reported.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Iranian government has pledged to shoulder the
cost of rebuilding all the roads and bridges destroyed in the
recent Israeli airstrikes on south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In later June, Israeli aircrafts bombed a number of key roads and
bridges connecting south Lebanon to Beriut, capital of the
country, in retaliation against Lebanese guerrillas's attacks on
Israeli targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
