<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian Police Collect Large Quantities of Looted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Albanian police have collected a
significant number of weapons in the town of Gramsh, 60 kilometers
southeast of Tirana, The Albanian Telegraphic Agency (ATA)
reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The collected weapons included 6,500 automatic rifles, 51,000
land mines and grenades, and 18 million bullets. They were part of
the arms looted by local residents during the turmoil throughout
Albania in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
Albanian police began to gather weapons in Gramsh about one
year ago under a United Nations-Sponsored pilot program called
"Handing Weapons for Development".
</P>
<P>
Under this program, the U.N. invested some 500,000 U.S. dollars
to help develop several projects on road construction,
establishment of telephone network, and rural development in
Gramsh in exchange of weapons from hands of local residents.
</P>
<P>
In early 1997, many angry Albanians stormed the military depots
around the country and took away many weapons after the
money-collecting pyramid scheme scandal burst, turning the country
to the edge of civil war.
</P>
<P>
Armed crimes recently were frequently reported in Albania. The
Albanian government currently is taking some measures to improve
the security around the country, including collecting looted
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
