<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Uses "Buy-back" Scheme to Develop Oil, Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran has succeeded in adopting
"buy-back" scheme to develop its oil and gas fields, and break
sanctions imposed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Tehran's pragmatist energy policy is succeeding, further
neutralizing American efforts to undermine Iran's economy," said
an official with the National Iranian Oil Company (NIOC).
</P>
<P>
Hojjatollah Ghanimifard, NIOC director for international
affairs, was quoted by local press as saying that Iran is
currently accepting tenders for the implementation of the phases
4-8 of the giant South Pars gas field in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The project attracted many foreign companies and the deadline
for the tender is set on September 1, he said.
</P>
<P>
This world's largest gas field lies 100 kilometers off Iran's
southern coast and has a reserve of about 8 trillion cubic meters
of gas. The whole project includes 10 drilling sites, two offshore
platforms and two lines of gas pipes of 105 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The "buy-back" scheme, also known as "service contract,"
promises contractors certain shares of oil and gas to compensate
their initial investments in exploration and development.
</P>
<P>
It is regarded by Iran as one of the best methods to conclude
energy deals, especially when the country is short of hard
currency.
</P>
<P>
The scheme's first application was with France' Total in
developing Sirri A and E oil fields in the Persian Gulf. With
Total's investment of 600 million U.S. dollars, the field came on
stream last autumn with a daily production capacity of more than
50,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
Ghanimifard said many foreign companies showed interest in
exploration. If a foreign company wins a tender, makes an
investment and succeeds in finding oil or gas, then project
development will be put on another tender, he explained.
</P>
<P>
"The company involved can get the new development phase if its
conditions are equal with those of the best bidder," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Iran has nominated Hussein Kazempour
Ardabili, top advisor to the oil minister, as its candidate for
the post of the next secretary-general of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Ardabili is also Iran's governor at OPEC and an advisor to
Iran's foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, on the other hand, has nominated its governor at
OPEC Soleiman al-Herbish as its candidate.
</P>
<P>
A final decision is expected at the next OPEC oil ministers'
meeting in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Court Maintains Verdict on MP Seats Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's Supreme Court on
Sunday rejected the parliament speaker's application seeking time
to study the court's verdict to refer the matter relating to the
floor crossing of two opposition law-makers to the Election
Commission (EC).
</P>
<P>
The court directed the speaker on July 29 to refer to the EC
within seven days the dispute as to whether the two
parliamentarians who have joined the government should vacate
their seats in line with the Constitution, dismissing an appeal
filed by the secretary of the Parliament Secretariat against the
High Court which directed the speaker to refer the dispute to the
EC within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
The speaker, who sought time before the Appellate Division of
the Supreme Court to study the court's decision and prayed for a
certified copy of the court's judgment, has already referred the
matter to the EC following the rejection of his time prayer by the
Supreme Court, the BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The court rejected the speaker's prayer Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On a writ petition filed by Khandker Delwar Hossain, chief whip
of the major opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP), and
Deputy leader of the opposition A.Q.M. Badruddoza Chowdhury, a
High Court Division Bench in August 1998 directed the speaker to
refer the matter of dispute over two BNP MPs' floor-crossing to
the EC within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
BNP members of parliament Alauddin Ahmed and Hasibur Rahman
Swapan took oath as ministers in the Awami League cabinet last
year.
</P>
<P>
Khandker Delwar Hossain and Badruddoza Chowdhury wrote letters
to the speaker to refer the matter of the two BNP lawmakers'
floor-crossing to the EC under article 70 of the country's
constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
