<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Launches Fresh Strikes Against Gunmen in Daghestan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian federal forces on Sunday
delivered fresh artillery and missile strikes on the positions of
several hundred gunmen who seized several villages in the
mountainous Botlikhsky district of Daghestan, which borders the
breakaway Chechnya republic.
</P>
<P>
Helicopter gunships and long-rang artillery were used in the
offensive against the gunmen that infiltrated into the villages
Saturday morning, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
There has been no report of casualties so far since federal
helicopter gunships and artillery pieces pounded the rebel
positions late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Russian Armed Forces General Staff Anatoly
Kvashnin, now in Daghestan, confirmed the strikes against the
gunmen, who are believed to be Islamic militants numbering 300 to
600 and under the command of Chechen field commanders Shamil
Basayev and Emir al-Hattab.
</P>
<P>
"We proceed from the need to avoid civilian casualties in our
strategy," Kvashnin said. "We will settle the gunmen problem but
no civilians will be harmed."
</P>
<P>
The gunmen are armed with two armored personnel carriers, an
anti-tank recoilless gun, air-defense systems and a huge amount of
firearms, Tass quoted a source in the Daghestani Interior Ministry
as saying.
</P>
<P>
They reportedly sneaked into the villages, disarmed the local
police and held the male population hostage while allowing women
and children to flee the area.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin has arrived in Makhachkala,
capital city of the Daghestan republic, to oversee the military
operation against the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
"Neither servicemen nor civilians must be harmed in settling
the situation in the Botlikhsky district," Stepashin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
