<HEADLINE> Today's Diplomatic News Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
diplomatic news today:
</P>
<P>
UNDP Regards China as a Strategic Partner
</P>
<P>
The United Nation Development Program (UNDP) considers China a
tremendous strategic partner and hopes to expand cooperation with
China, Mark Brown, its administrator, told a group of Chinese
journalists this morning.
</P>
<P>
Brown came here on August 5 at the invitation of Shi Guangsheng,
the Chinese minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation,
and he met with President Jiang Zemin and other officials on
August 6.
</P>
<P>
China Supports Colombian Peace Process
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi said here today that
the Chinese government supports the peace process in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Yang told a delegation from the House of Representatives of
Colombia, headed by Sergio Cabrera, that China appreciates the
efforts made by the Colombian government and people toward
national reconciliation, improved economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
China believes that the Colombian peace process helps the
country's political stability, economic development, and improved
standard of living, he said. China hopes the goal can be achieved
at an early date.
</P>
<P>
CPPCC Vice-Chairman Meets Panamanian Visitors
</P>
<P>
Li Guixian, vice-chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), met
here today with former Panamanian Vice President Ricardo Arias
Calderon and his party.
</P>
<P>
Li said that although the two countries have not established
diplomatic ties, the two peoples enjoy a traditional friendship.
He added that the two countries can promote mutual understanding
and friendship by increasing exchanges, so as to push forward the
process of normalization of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Sino-U.S.Youth "Root Seeking Tour" Begins
</P>
<P>
A ceremony to mark the beginning of the '99 Chinese-American
Youth "Root Seeking Tour" was held here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 Chinese American kids from California of the
United States will tour such cities as Beijing, Shanghai and Xi'an
and participate in activities of cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The Root Seeking Tour is sponsored by the Overseas Chinese
Affairs Office of the State Council with the help of two U.S.
Chinese language schools to mark the 50th anniversary of the
founding of New China and the forthcoming Macao's return to the
motherland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
