<HEADLINE> Vietnam Intensifies Fight Against Drug-Related Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has detected 7,625
drug-related cases with 15,710 people involved over the past seven
months, showing increases of 53.2 percent and 52.6 percent
respectively over the same period last year, Vietnam News Agency
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
As a result, more than 44 kg of heroin, 284 kg of opium and 297
kg of marijuana were seized.
</P>
<P>
According to Vietnam's Committee for Nationalities and
Mountainous Areas, the government has increased inspections of
poppy growing areas and encouraged local people to eradicate and
replace poppy plants with other food and industrial crops for
socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
Almost 9,000 drug addicts were treated in detoxification
centers nationwide and 3,400 others in communities.
</P>
<P>
Drug abuse prevention has been strengthened under commitments
signed between pupils, school masters, parents and local police.
Drug abuse issues have also been added to school curricula.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that heroin and other drugs are transported to
Vietnam mainly through borders with neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
To boost the fight against drug-related crimes, Vietnam's
police have this year coordinated with Interpol and foreign forces
in detecting more than 30 drug trafficking cases. Vietnamese
police officially joined a criminal information system including
ASEANAPOL in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam now has 90,000 drug addicts under monitoring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
