<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Accepts OAU Proposal on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Eritrea has officially accepted
the proposal on Technical Arrangements by the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) submitted to Eritrea at the weekend aimed at
ending the bloody war with neighboring Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean Foreign Affairs Ministry said in a press release
that it has also"pledged its full cooperation with the OAU and the
United Nations in implementing the three agreements -- the
Framework Agreement, the Modalities and Technical Arrangements."
</P>
<P>
The three documents are the sole basis for resolving the
Ethio-Eritrean dispute, said the press release available here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean President Isaias Afewerki informed the OAU delegation
led by Algerian special envoy Ahmed Ouyahya of Eritrea's
acceptance during a meeting in Asmara Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean president had also sent Eritrea's official and
written acceptance to the Algerian President and current OAU
chairman Abdelaziz Bouteflika, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The Technical Arrangements were worked out by technical experts
from Algeria, the OAU, the U.N. and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean Foreign Ministry said the envisaged next steps are
a formal signature of all three documents, a cessation of
hostilities, redeployment of troops, the instatement of civilian
administrations and demarcation within specific time frames.
</P>
<P>
The OAU mediation delegation left Asmara Sunday for Addis Ababa
for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
The war between Eritrea and Ethiopia broke out on May 6, 1998
over a disputed stretch of their border area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
