<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retiring S. African Central Banker Gives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Retiring South African
Reserve Bank governor Chris Stals gave his commandments of central
banking Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Handing over the central bank reigns to former labor minister
Tito Mboweni at midnight Saturday, Stals listed his commandments
at a gala banquet in Midrand, north of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
He said the need for the central bank's independence must be
recognized and appreciated by the public and by governments. But,
after all was said and done, a central bank could only be as
independent as the government of the day wanted it to be.
</P>
<P>
"From my experience, I have learned that without regular
contact and close cooperation with the minister of finance, the
life of a central banker can become very lonely."
</P>
<P>
He said in many countries of the world, the central bank's
powers should be reduced to increase the effectiveness of monetary
policy.
</P>
<P>
"Joined with the potent power to create money, the power to
make loans and spend money has the potential to create a
superpower, whose actions can easily lead to financial
destruction."
</P>
<P>
He said, by successfully restricting growth in the total
domestic assets of the central bank, monetary policy would ensure
growth in the total foreign assets of the country.
</P>
<P>
A central banker was often very unpopular in his country, and
if the governor did become popular in his own country, it might be
the time for him to retire.
</P>
<P>
"Monetary policy is about financial discipline, about
restricting expenditure, about forcing the country to live within
its means. Measures to achieve these objectives can never be
popular. You cannot ask the turkeys of the world to vote for
Christmas. You also cannot ask of money what the level of interest
rates should be."
</P>
<P>
Stals said: "When I was criticized for the policies of the
bank, I always asked who the critic was and where he worked. That
normally made me apathetic.
</P>
<P>
"A country may be able to keep politicians out of interest
rates, but you can never take interest rates out of politics.
When politicians therefore make statements about interest rates,
central bankers should infer that they are talking to their
voters, and not to the central bank."
</P>
<P>
There was no such thing as central banking by rules, he said,
adding discretion remained indispensable in the daily
implementation of monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
"Economics, after all, is not an exact science. In the world
of macro- economic policy, two plus two may sometimes add up to
five. As a central banker, never, however, try to make it six."
</P>
<P>
The outgoing governor pointed out that a central banker must
learn to ignore any praise bestowed on him, particularly through
or by the media.
</P>
<P>
"This will justify his right also to resent the unfair
criticism that will be launched at him from the same sources."
</P>
<P>
In the present world of a rapidly changing global financial
environment, a central banker must be a student for ever, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Always remember the old Chinese saying that a man must study
as if he will live forever, but live as if he will die tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
Stals said these ten commandments represented for him a final
conclusion of his experience as a central banker over many years.
</P>
<P>
He was leaving the bank "in great peace of mind" because he was
 confident that Mboweni and his bank team had the ability,
determination and the will to steer South Africa successfully into
"this brave new world".
</P>
<P>
Stals paid tribute to the South African bankers who he said did
not always agree with the bank's hard-line approach, but always
remained loyal to it.
</P>
<P>
He also thanked people he worked with over many years as a
central banker, including government people, as well as the
previous presidents who appointed him deputy governor, senior
deputy governor and later governor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> INLA Declares War Is Over: Paper Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 8 (Xinhua)-- The Irish National Liberation Army
(INLA) has become the first paramilitary group in Northern Ireland
to declare its war is over, according to a newspaper report.
</P>
<P>
The INLA, which came to prominence in 1979 when it killed
Conservative MP Airey Neave in a car bomb, has told its political
wing, the Irish Republican Socialist Party (IRSP), it has no
reason to continue its armed campaign, The Sunday Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a senior party member as saying, "The INLA
have assured us that as far as they are concerned the war is over
and they see no further basis for armed struggle."
</P>
<P>
The group is also reported to have rejected attempts by
republican groups the Continuity IRA and the Real IRA to join them
in a bombing campaign in mainland Britain.
</P>
<P>
However, the INLA is believed instead to be promoting the idea
of a non-aggression pact with the province's largest republican
group, the IRA, and mainstream loyalist paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
The INLA declared a ceasefire on August 22 last year after a
bloody campaign of violence which saw several feuds within the
organization.
</P>
<P>
But before its ceasefire was called, its members carried out
the murder of one of the province's most feared loyalist
paramilitary leaders, Billy Wright, in the Maze Prison in December
1997.
</P>
<P>
There has been a cautious response to the report from unionist
politicians. Ulster Unionist MP Jeffrey Donaldson said he would be
adopting "a wait and see approach."
</P>
<P>
"If the INLA are calling a complete end to their campaign of
violence, then it follows like day follows night that they will
have to decommission," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
