<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Capital to Host Hi-tech Center for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA) is preparing to set up a Technology
Center for Africa at its headquarters in Ethiopian capital Addis
Ababa, business weekly Capital reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The technology center, designed to create a bridge between the
African continent and the rest of the world, will be situated at
the 120-million- dollar U.N. Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
The founding of the technology center will be a major step
toward the realization of the African Information Society
Initiative, a structural framework for developing Africa's
information and communication infrastructure, ECA officials said.
</P>
<P>
The information society initiative was adopted in Addis Ababa
in 1996 by African ministers in charge of economic development and
planning.
</P>
<P>
According to a brochure issued by the ECA, the technology
center, due to be officially launched in October 1999, will
consist of two distinctive components, the Technology Exhibition
Center and the Training Center.
</P>
<P>
The former will demonstrate information and communication
technology applications, and will display services and products
including hardware and software computer products, computer-based
training, video and audio conference and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
The latter, while providing workshops, seminars and scholarship
on information and communication technology for the different
parties involved in the African development process, will mainly
target technical managers, policy makers, and planers including
delegates of African countries attending conferences at the Addis
Ababa-based U.N. Conference Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
