<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sweeps Gold and Silver in Table Tennis Worlds  By Sportswriter Cao Jianjie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 8 (Xinhua) -- China scored a clean
sweep of the gold and silver medals at the world table tennis
championships on Sunday as two penholders made the men's singles final
as an all-Chinese affair.
</P>
<P>
Ma Lin and Liu Guoliang, who both play in penhold grip, beat
handshakers Jan-Ove Waldner and Werner Schlager in the semifinals,
rejuvenating what once had been branded as outdated as the wooden
tennis racket, the scissor-style high jump and bowling underarm in
cricket.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, China has secured a gold-silver sweep in the women's
singles, women's doubles, men's doubles and mixed doubles, with Wang
Nan emerging winner both in the women's singles and doubles.
</P>
<P>
Dual Olympic champion Liu Guoliang, who combined with Kong Linghui
to win the men's doubles trophy on Saturday, handed a 21-10, 21-18,
18-21, 21-16 defeat to Schlager, a quarter-final winner over two-time
World Cup champion Zoran Primorac of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Ma Lin, who has taken the mixed doubles title with Zhang Yingying,
came from two sets down and 10-15 behind in the third set to outlast
Waldner 18-21, 14-21, 21-19, 21-19, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Swede, the only player in the world to have won a
"Grand Slam" of Olympic, world championship and World Cup titles, used
his deceptive serves and follow-up topspin strokes to clinch the first
two sets easily.
</P>
<P>
Ma came back strongly, unleashing a string of devastating forehand
attacks to win three sets in a row, while Walnder looked nervous and
missed quite a few easy kills.
</P>
<P>
"My secret to win? Nothing! I just didn't want to lose," the
19-year-old Ma said.
</P>
<P>
"I broke Waldner's nerves when I came back from 10-15 down to win
the third set. In the last two sets, I was so nervous that my arms
felt stiff, but Waldner was more nervous than I."
</P>
<P>
Yao Zhenxu, vice chairman of the Chinese Table Tennis Association,
said Ma's steel nerves played a crucial role in his win over Waldner,
the man who brong down China's 1995 world champion Kong Linghui and
still holds many Chinese in awe.
</P>
<P>
"In technical terms, Walnder is much better than Ma, but Ma is
mentally stronger than Waldner although the Swede usually displays
excellent poise and balance," Yao said.
</P>
<P>
"Two Chinese in final means a lot to Chinese table tennis. We have
been waiting for this moment for very long time," Yao added.
</P>
<P>
Since Chinese Jiang Jialiang grabbed his second world title in
1989, Europeans had dominated the men's singles event until 1995, when
Kong Linghui cashed in on home-court advantage to win the most
valuable title in table tennis. China lost the event in the 1997
championships as Waldner and Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus shut the
Chinese out of the final.
</P>
<P>
"Our efforts to improve skills and find new talents has never
stopped. That's why we are so strong," Yao said.
</P>
<P>
Ma and Liu has proven, with their wins over top Europeans, that
Chinese penhold style is still a lethal weapon.
</P>
<P>
The two styles play as their names suggest. A handshaker grips
the bat as of if he is shaking someone's hand and can easily make
forehand and backhand strokes.
</P>
<P>
A traditional penholder uses only one side of the bat for both
strokes and grips the bat as if holding a pen. This style is well
suited for flat forehands and defensive dropshots but is short on
backhand power.
</P>
<P>
Unlike traditional penholders, both Liu and Ma stick rubber onto
both sides of the bat and plays top spin with backhand.
</P>
<P>
"I can't say now that penhold is superior to handshake, but I can
say for sure that penhold is never a sporting bygone," Yao Zhenxu
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
