<HEADLINE> Shirov Ties Milos in World Chess Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Second-seeded Alexei Shirov of
Spain failed to convert his opening game win and tied with No. 50
seed Gilbert Milos of Brazil in the third round of the World Chess
Championship in Las Vegas on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Needing only a draw to advance, Shirov played passively at the
beginning of the game Saturday, while Milos advanced on Shirov's
central pawns and was about to win a bishop when Shirov resigned.
</P>
<P>
All other six players who won their first games of round three
on Friday, advanced to the next round in the seven-round 3-million
dollars monthlong tournament.
</P>
<P>
And sixth-seeded Vassily Ivanchuk of the Ukraine was the only
one of the six to win the second game of his mini-matches by
dispatching Russia's Sergei Shipov, the 22nd seed.
</P>
<P>
Those advanced included Alexei Fedorov of Belarus, Nigel Short
of Britain, Bulgarians Veselin Topalov and Kiril Georgiev, Vadim
Zvjaginsev of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Several players who drew their first game of this round secured
theirs place in the fourth round with victories on Saturday,
including Hungary's Judit Polgar, the only woman remaining in the
tournament, who beat Jordi Magem Badals of Spain.
</P>
<P>
Others included top-seeded Vladimir Kramnik of Russia, Michael
Adams of Britain, and Alexander Khalifman of Russia who was the
only player to advance by winning with the black pieces.
</P>
<P>
Aleksey Dreev upset his countryman Sergei Rublevsky to advance.
</P>
<P>
Eight players of Sergei Movsesian of the Czech Republic, Peter
Leko of Hungary, Vladimir Akopian of Armenia, Evgeny Bareev of
Russia, Boris Gelfand of Israel, Joel Lautier of France, Romania's
Liviu Nisipeanu and Brazil's seed Rafael Leitao drawed their two
games and will play the playoff matches on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
