<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scheme Launched to Offer On-Line Government Services (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The scheme will allow filing of simple tax returns or payment
of tax through the Internet at any time.
</P>
<P>
The existing 1.23 million drivers and 500,000 vehicle owners
can renew their driving and vehicle licenses respectively through
the on-line services.
</P>
<P>
The other seven government departments are: Immigration, Labor,
Rating and Valuation, Industry and Social Welfare Departments,
Registration and Electoral Office as well as Treasury.
</P>
<P>
Using their electronic services, to cite a few, job-seekers can
look for job vacancies while employers can submit job vacancies
and search for suitable candidates. Those eligible can register as
voters, and individuals can book appointments for identity card
registration.
</P>
<P>
Members of the public will be able to apply on-line for
volunteer scheme registration and senior citizen cards. Businesses
can seek advice on investment and business licensing requirements.
Tourists can access information about Hong Kong. Users can pay tax,
rates, government rent and water charges electronically.
</P>
<P>
The ESD Scheme will also be operated at a cross-departmental
level in a seamless manner. At present, citizens have to notify
individual departments of any change in their personal particulars,
such as addresses, separately.
</P>
<P>
ESD is a key initiative under the "Digital 21" Information
Technology Strategy which aims at enhancing and promoting Hong
Kong's information infrastructure and services, making it a
leading digital city in the globally connected world of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Siu noted that the introduction of ESD would pave the way for
the development of electronic commerce in Hong Kong with the
government's promotional efforts.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a public key infrastructure, supported by
certification authorities, and a clear legal framework for
electronic transactions will further boost public confidence and
provide a secure environment conducive to electronic commerce
locally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scheme Launched to Offer On-Line Government Services in HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- No one can resist a scheme
that will bring to them a substantial saving in time, labor and
traveling expenses in obtaining government services as compared
with the conventional means of visiting government offices and
queuing for counter service during office hours.
</P>
<P>
The Electronic Service Delivery (ESD) Scheme, to be launched in
the latter half of next year, will offer these advantages.
</P>
<P>
"Under the ESD Scheme, the public will be able to enjoy
efficient, better quality and round-the-clock service seven days a
week provided by the Government on-line through personal computers
at home or computers installed at District Offices, public
libraries, community halls and centers throughout Hong Kong, or
other electronic means," said Alan Siu, principal assistant
secretary of the Information Technology and Broadcasting Bureau (
ITBB).
</P>
<P>
A total of 37 services will be delivered electronically by nine
government departments along with Hong Kong Tourist Association (
HKTA) in Phase I of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
This involves an allocation of capital and staff costs totaling
150.8 million HK dollars (about 19.3 million U.S. dollars) by the
Finance Committee of the Legislative Council, Siu said.
</P>
<P>
"Six consortia comprising local and overseas companies have
tendered for the supply of the ESD Scheme. We are now scrutinizing
the tenders on the basis of their technical expertise and
financial implication," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We will award the contract around the end of September or
early October this year. The successful bidder has to complete the
project within 12 months."
</P>
<P>
To widen the scope of the scheme, Siu said, the contractor can
extend its services to the private sector at a later stage after
the introduction of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
"ITBB will monitor the operation of the scheme and review the
progress within three years of its implementation. The extent of
provision of conventional counter service will be assessed," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Inland Revenue and Transport Departments are expected to top
the list of nine government departments in carrying the largest
volume of electronic transactions with the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
