<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Exhibition Captures Scent of Qing Dynasty Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition featuring a
selection of Chinese women paintings in the 19th century is staged
at the Historical Pictures Gallery of the Hong Kong Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Leisure Pursuits: Paintings of Qing Dynasty Women,"
the exhibition gives viewers a glance of domestic life at the time.
It also provides the viewers with an opportunity to admire a
variety of women images in different styles created by Chinese and
Western artists.
</P>
<P>
From the 23 paintings on display, viewers may learn that the
Chinese artists still followed the traditional style of lady
paintings, according to a staff member of the museum.
</P>
<P>
Most of the ladies were painted with stylized facial features
and were always depicted as gentle, sedate and quiet. In the mean
time, slenderness was the Chinese aesthetic standard of woman, the
staff member said.
</P>
<P>
The painting "The Empress of China" by the Chinese artist
Tingqua is one of the examples in which the woman is presented as
slim figures dressed in loosen clothes, and facial expression is
minimal yet calm.
</P>
<P>
The staff member said that in contrast, the Western artists
devoted much effort on capturing the movement, individual
personality and expression of emotion in their paintings.
</P>
<P>
Like the "Dame Chinoise" drawn by the French artist Deveria A.
and lithographed by Lemercier, it displays how the Europeans
reconstructed their own Chinese beauty with sensuous female
figures and how they projected their own ideal images of Qing
women in the paintings, he added.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will run until the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt Urged To Set up Breast-feeding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Federal and state governments of
Nigeria have been urged to establish centers in their various
departments and offices where nursing mothers in their employment
can breast-feed their children during working hours.
</P>
<P>
Medical Director of the Federal Medical Center Hussein
Aladesawe made the call Saturday at the opening ceremony of
Breast-feeding Week organized by the center in Owo, Nigeria's
southeastern Ondo State.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government should actively participate in the
campaign for total breast-feeding of all children from birth till
six months as there are complaints of inadequate breast-feeding of
Nigerian children in the early stage.
</P>
<P>
Since it is difficult for the government to grant women
maternity leave beyond the normal three months, the centers would
have, among other things, a qualified nurse who would ensure that
these babies are well fed for the initial six months, the Guardian
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Since children are the future leaders of the nation and the
hope for our continuity, it is mandatory for us to ensure that
their development is not allowed to suffer or be tampered with in
any way", Aladesawe was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that once a child is taking adequate breast milk, such
a child does not need water or any other food or medicaments.
</P>
<P>
He explained that breast milk contains adequate food
complements, stressing that "an unhealthy child will normally
develop into an unhealthy adult."
</P>
<P>
He commended the Federal Ministry of Health and the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) for their financial and moral
support given to the management of the center toward organizing
celebrations for the World Breast-feeding Week.
</P>
<P>
He assured the UNICEF that whatever assistance given to the
center would be used in propagation of Breast-feeding in Owo Local
Government Area in particular and the state in general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
