<HEADLINE> HK to Launch New Publicity Campaign to Fight Youth Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- A new round of government
publicity against youth crime will be launched in the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region this month, a spokesman for the
Fight Crime Committee said.
</P>
<P>
To sustain the publicity efforts of last year's Fight Youth
Crime Campaign, the campaign this year will again focus on parent-
child relationship, and promote mutual understanding between the
two generations, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"Parents are urged to provide more support and guidance for
their children, especially when their children have emotional
problems. And children, on the other hand, should put themselves
in their parents' shoes and try to understand the feelings of
their parents," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that some 33,140 crimes were detected in HK
in 1998, with 40,422 people arrested for various criminal offenses.
Of those arrested, 5,834 were juvenile offenders, aged between
seven and 15, and 6,613 were young persons, accounting for 32
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
On this year's publicity campaign, the spokesman said the
messages on prevention of juvenile crime will be delivered to
members of the public through a range of channels. These include
two 30-second promotional films on television, or Television
Announcements in the Public Interest, radio messages, magazine
advertisements and posters.
</P>
<P>
The films are reinforced by advertisements targeted at children.
While advertisements will be placed in magazines well received by
youngsters, the promotional films will also be screened in cinemas.
Besides, posters echoing the theme will be displayed along the
tracks of the Mass Transit Railway. A number of buses and trams
will be painted with the fight youth crime messages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
