<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran intends to add 250,000 new mobile phone lines to
its telecom network before the end of the Iranian year next March.
</P>
<P>
"The number of lines will be increased from 430,000 to more
than 680,000," said Director of Iran's State Telephone Company,
Abdollah Mir-Taheri.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that more than 3 million mobile numbers
will be operational within the next five years. Since Iran has a
population of more than 60 million, that will mean one mobile
phone for more than 20 people.
</P>
<P>
Iran's mobile phone network, which uses GSM standard
technology, covers almost all of the nation's major cities and
towns.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran is to hold it first exclusive exhibition in
Almaty, Kazakhstan next week to promote the sale of Iranian goods
in the former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will put on show pharmaceuticals, foodstuff,
vegetable oil, ironwork of doors and windows, taps, valves and
faucets, asbestos, accumulators, oysters and picture frames,
electric switches and sockets, wire and cables, paints, minibuses,
factory-woven carpets, stone slabs for building purposes, tiles,
ovens, plastic and household appliances, chinaware, and steel
utensils.
</P>
<P>
Annual trade volume between Iran and Kazakhstan is now valued
at 100 million U.S. dollars, in which Kazakhstan's exports amount
to 60 million and those of Iran, 40 million.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudan is in need of about 2 billion U.S. dollars
for the construction of new dams and the expansion of existing
ones.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has drawn up a comprehensive national strategy for the
development of water resources which covers the Atbara River, the
Blue Nile and the Nile River, said Sudanese Minister of Irrigation
and Water Resources Kamal Ali Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
Plans have been made to build two more dams along the Atbara
River and on the Nile River to generate electricity and to promote
cultivation.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government is currently seeking for necessary
funding from international markets and financial organizations for
the implementation of these projects.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The overall growth rate of Sudan's economy during
the past year stood at 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector made remarkable increase in the area
under cultivation for 40 million feddans (16.8 million hectars) as
compared to 18 million feddans (7.56 million hectars) two years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
A recent report on the performance of Sudan's economy
attributed the growth to a policy based on cutting taxes on
company profits, lowering of the production and sales taxes in
order to boost local industries and promoting the competitiveness
of the Sudanese goods in face of imported commodities, the Arab
economic daily Alam Al Yom reported Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
