<HEADLINE> Islamic Gunmen Continue Control Russian Villages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Islamic extremists who crossed
into Russia's Daghestan from the breakaway Chechnya republic
Saturday continue to hold positions around the mountain villages
of Ansalta and Rokhota in Dagestan's Botlikh district, the
Interfax news agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An officer of the Dagestani Interior Ministry's Border
Department said the situation did not change and was relatively
tranquil Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen, with fire arms and anti-tank and antiaircraft
weapons, are being countered by the local police, special units,
and units of the Russian Interior Ministry's 102nd interior
brigade and of the Defense Ministry's 136th motorized infantry
brigade, supported by helicopters.
</P>
<P>
The Dagestani law-enforcement bodies will hold a large-scale
operation against the Muslim gunmen later Sunday, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The decision to launch such an operation was taken Saturday
night by the headquarters of the Dagestani law-enforcement bodies
led by Interior Minister Adilgerei Magomedtagirov, and Commander
of the Russian Interior Troops Vladimir Ovchinnikov.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Commander-in-Chief of Russia's Interior Troops
Vyacheslav Ovchinnikov has also flown to the Botlikhsky district,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported, quoting the Daghestan regional
interior ministry's press service.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and Chief
of the Russian General Staff Anatoly Kvashnin are also coming to
Daghestan later Sunday to oversee the fight against the Islamic
infiltrators, believed to be headed by Chechen rebel field
commanders Shamil Basayev and Emir al-Hattab.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin will fly from Kazan, Tatarstan, to the Dagestani
capital of Makhachkala in a mission agreed upon by telephone with
President Boris Yeltsin, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Tass reported that virtually all villagers of Ansalta and
Rakhata, around which the gunmen entrenched themselves, have fled
their homes. Some of the refugees, mainly women and children,
arrived in the Daghestan capital Makhschkala Saturday night, Tass
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Daghestan authorities have urged the citizens "to preserve
vigilance and calm and do not fall in for provocation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
