<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Asks Albright to Postpone Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak last week asked U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
to postpone her planned Middle East trip due to the impasse in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, local media reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to reports by The Jerusalem Post and Haaretz
newspapers, Barak wished that the dispute between Israel and the
Palestinians over the timing of the implementation of the Wye
agreement can be resolved locally before Albright's visit.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz newspaper said that Barak's call on Thursday to
Albright was also aimed at focusing Albright's trip, originally
scheduled for 14-18 this month, on pushing forward the
Israeli-Syrian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
And Washington is reportedly considering postponing the trip
until the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, no advance teams for Albright's visit are in Israel
yet.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post quoted a spokesman at the U.S. Embassy in
Tel Aviv as saying that Albright is still planning to visit the
region this month, only "the dates haven't been finalized."
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) signed the
Wye interim accords in the United States last October, which
requires Israel to hand over to the Palestinians 13.1 percent of
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Netanyahu, Barak's hard-line predecessor, carried out
the first phase of the three-stage withdrawal, but then suspended
the accord, accusing the Palestinians of failing to fulfill their
security commitments.
</P>
<P>
After taking office last month, Barak pledged to implement the
second stage of the withdrawal, but proposed to combine the third
phase withdrawal with the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak also told Israel Television on Friday that Israel would
start the implementation of the Wye agreement within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had agreed in meetings last month with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat to put the stalled agreement back into action starting in
September.
</P>
<P>
However, Palestinians said they have not been informed of a
new timetable and would accept it only if the remaining two
redeployments were made on schedule.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Palestinian cabinet after its weekly
meeting on Friday said Palestinians would not enter "final status
talks until the honest and complete implementation of interim
agreements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
