<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebels Kill 7 Ugandan Soldiers in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Goma faction of the split
Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) of the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC), reportedly killed seven Ugandan soldiers in eastern
Congo in intensified clashes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The fighting, which pits RCD rebels backed by Rwanda and based
in Goma against Ugandan troops backing a rival rebel faction,
occurred in the northern city of Kisangani, the Monitor daily
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
There were reports indicating some seven Ugandan soldiers might
have been killed and many other causalities on the other side, a
top security source was quoted as saying Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan contingent, led by Ugandan Chief of Staff James
Kazini, shelled the bases of their rivals with heavy weapons, the
RCD Vice President Jean-Pierre Ondekane said.
</P>
<P>
An information officer with the rebel group said that Ugandan
officers passing in front of the house of a rebel officer opened
fire without warning, provoking a response from the Congolese
guard.
</P>
<P>
The report, however, did not give explanations of the exchange
of gunfire from the Ugandan side.
</P>
<P>
The RCD, the main rebel group opposing Congolese President
Laurent Kabila, split on May 19, when its president Wamba dia
Wamba was replaced by Emile IIIunga.
</P>
<P>
Uganda backs Wamba dia Wamba, whose base is in Kisangani, while
Rwanda has thrown its support behind IIIunga, who has his
headquarters in Goma.
</P>
<P>
Wamba demanded he has the right to sign on behalf of the RCD a
cease- fire accord reached in Zambian capital Lusaka on July 10,
while IIIunga and the RCD-Goma faction denied him the authority
and refused to endorse the pact themselves until the question has
been settled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
