<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Has First Black Central Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Former labor minister Tito
Mboweni has been inaugurated as new governor of the South African
Reserve Bank, becoming the first black central banker in South
African history.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni, 40, took over the Reserve Bank reigns from Chris Stals
on the stroke of midnight Saturday at a gala banquet in Midrand,
north of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
South African President Thabo Mbeki called Mboweni's
inauguration "an important day in our history." He also praised
Stals, saying that he facilitated transmission.
</P>
<P>
The president said that when former president Nelson Mandela
asked Stals to stay on for another five years in 1994, Stals had
no hesitation in doing so.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki noted that Stals similarly had no hesitation in
supporting Mboweni, who was transferred to the central bank as
governor-in-waiting from his labor portfolio a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni told the banquet that his appointment did not "herald
the start of a cheap money era in the bank."
</P>
<P>
He also said the South African Reserve Bank was not an Icarus
that would fly too close to the sun.
</P>
<P>
"Emerging markets globally have suffered financial turmoil
which plunged many into deep recession. South Africa, though
resilient, has not emerged from this turmoil unscathed. At only
half-a-percent, the rate of growth in gross domestic product last
year fell woefully short of the levels needed in a country where
poverty and joblessness remain widespread.
</P>
<P>
"Against this background, it is hardly surprising that people
sometimes express the hope that the Reserve Bank will take action
to stimulate economic growth by printing money. Some think that as
a former cabinet minister my appointment heralds the start of a
cheap money era in the bank. Quite simply, they are wrong.
</P>
<P>
"Our view has been, and will continue to be, that it is not our
role to provide an artificial stimulus for the economy. The role
of the bank is to create a climate of financial stability in which
economic growth and wealth creation will be sustainable; an
environment in which an economic boom will not be followed by an
inevitable bust."
</P>
<P>
On monetary policy frameworks, Mboweni commented: "Some central
banks have adopted currency boards to fix their exchange rates,
while others follow exchange rate targeting or inflation
targeting. We have to design our approach bearing in mind our
experiences and history, but also taking into account what is
international best practice which has delivered financial
stability and acceptable levels of inflation."
</P>
<P>
Stals expressed confidence in Mboweni.
</P>
<P>
"Looking ahead, I can only express my regrets that I were not
10 years younger. Exciting times lie ahead for the central bankers
of the world as the process of the integration of financial
markets around the globe will continue," he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, I leave the South African Reserve Bank in great peace
of mind because I am confident that Tito Mboweni and the team with
him in the Bank have the ability, the determination and the will
to steer South Africa successfully into this brave new world,"
Stals added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
