<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Positive Signs Rise in S. Leone Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- S. Leone's former military junta
chief Major General Johnny Koromah said Saturday that he had
ordered his supporters to free the about 30 hostages held in the
hills some 60 kilometers east of the country's capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Koromah said in a British Broadcast Corporation (BBC) interview
Saturday that "I told them to make sure they release them today
without any precondition. They've accepted that they are going to
release them including the Children" , who were abducted earlier.
</P>
<P>
The BBC said Koromah, the leader of the Armed Forces
Revolutionary Council, was now in Liberia's capital Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
The leader said he had told the rebels taking the hostages
that, contrary to their belief, he was not being held prisoner by
the Foday Sankoh-led Revolutionary United Front (RUF) rebel group.
</P>
<P>
His release had been one of the hostage takers's key demands.
</P>
<P>
"I am not a prisoner at all. I am a free man," Koromah said in
the radio interview.
</P>
<P>
The Revolutionary United Front has also denied holding Koromah
Saturday, saying that it has been working closely with the Armed
forces Revolutionary Council, an old ally of it.
</P>
<P>
Koromah said he would try to meet Sankoh to prove to his own
rebels that he was a free man, and hopefully trigger the hostages'
release.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh said in Freetown Saturday that the kidnapping was an
"isolated" incident that did not signal a broader split in the
rebels' alliance.
</P>
<P>
He also accused the U.N. and the west Africa peace-keeping
force ECOMOG officials of carelessly provoking the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said they had failed to contact senior rebel officials
before sending the delegation into rebel-held territory.
</P>
<P>
The kidnapping took place Wednesday when an international group
 including U.N officials, ECOMOG soldiers, Sierra Leonean
officials, and journalists met with soldiers loyal to Koromah to
receive about 150 women and children captured during the war.
</P>
<P>
The junta soldiers freed several captives Thursday, including
two U.N. officials, a Reuters reporter and an clergy man,
requiring them to convey their demands for food, medicine, and the
release of their leader among others.
</P>
<P>
Koromah, a former military officer, launched a coup and fought
himself to the Head of State in 1997 and allied itself with the
Sankoh's rebels, which has been fighting successive governments
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
But 10 month latter, he was flushed out by the Nigeria-led
ECOMOG and the unseated President Tejan Kabbah was reinstated.
</P>
<P>
Despite Sankoh's constant calling of Koromah as the "number two
man" in the rebel alliance, it is widely believed that Koromah and
his men might feel sidelined by a July 7 peace agreement signed in
Togolese capital Lome by Sankoh and Sierra Leonean President
Kabbah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
