<HEADLINE> Saddam Accuses Iran of Retaining Iraqi POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
on Sunday accused Iran of retaining thousands of Iraqi prisoners
of war (POWs) and refusing to register some of them at the Red
Cross.
</P>
<P>
Saddam uttered the accusation in a nationally televised speech
marking the 11th anniversary of the end of the 1980-1988 Iraq-Iran
war.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq released all Iranian POWs a short time after ceasefire,
except one POW who was later set free. Iran, up to now, has
retained thousands of Iraqi POWs," said the president.
</P>
<P>
Saddam also accused Iran of torturing, mistreating and
murdering Iraqi POWs.
</P>
<P>
"Our heroes of POWs have received and are still receiving
various kinds of torture and pressure, many a time they have been
murdered inside the captivity cages," he said.
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs has been an outstanding obstacle that stands
in the way of normalizing ties between the two former foes which
fought a bitter eight-year war in which nearly 1 million people
were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Saddam also slammed the U.S. and its allies for
adopting destructive approach toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Some have dogfought against Baghdad with hatred and envy and
have employed forces, some of which are backward, for
destruction, while others have used their accumulation of malice
and narrow, greedy interests to portray to the backward that
their destructive approach is right," he said.
</P>
<P>
Saddam lashed out at the materialism adopted "by the west under
the leadership of U.S.A. in the Middle East region and perhaps in
other places." 
</P>
</TEXT>
