<HEADLINE> Kenya to Destroy Drug Farms by Chemicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is
considering using chemicals to clear the bhang plantations in
Mount Kenya in central part of this east African country.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jackobam, head of the Kenya Anti-Narcotics Unit, said
here Saturday that his unit is working with Kenya Wildlife
Service, the Defense Department and the relevant ministries to
conduct aerial surveys in the forest and launch the program.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Nation newspaper quoted Jackobam as saying that
although the exercise would be expensive, the unit had enough
resources to wipe out the plant in two months.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a workshop on drug and drug-related offenses
organized by the Kenya Magistrates and Judges Association,
Jackobam said that lack of information and cooperation from
civilians had hampered effective operation of his unit and
appealed to all Kenyans, together with the police, to deal with
the issues of drugs.
</P>
<P>
He told the participants that his unit planned to set up
additional stations in the country, particularly in the Mount
Kenya region and the Moi Airport in Eldoret in western Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the police in Kenya's Eastern Province discovered
more than 1, 500 acres of land are under bhang plantation in Mount
Kenya forest as police are intensifying operation to rid the
forest of drug farms.
</P>
<P>
According to the Criminal Investigations Department, the Kenyan
police recently seized 44 tons of bhang and arrested 27 suspects
of illegal drug peddling in separate cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
