<HEADLINE> South African Conmen Swindle Zambia of Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Four white South African conmen
posing as International Police (Interpol) agents swindled Zambia
Revenue Authority (ZRA) of five new vehicles last week, according
to Sunday Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The four who appeared at a ZRA port brandishing fake Interpol
identity cards and produced a list of vehicles they claimed had
been stolen from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
They were later led by Zambian officials for a physical
inspection of the cars where they identified the vehicles they
were after.
</P>
<P>
They allegedly made false entries in a log book before getting
away with the cars and sped off in the direction of Chirundu
border post 200 kilometers from Zambian capital Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Alex Chilufya confirmed the incident, saying
that Interpol Zambia has taken up the issue and alerted their
colleagues in the region to be on the lookout.
</P>
<P>
He said the mastermind of the syndicate, whom he named, was a
former police officer in Souther Africa who knows the ropes on the
dealings of Interpol and had allegedly used an insider at the ZRA
management over the matter. 
</P>
