<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Police Hunting for Safari Bandits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The police are launching an
 intensive manhunt for three bandits who robbed 17 Spanish
tourists last Monday at a village in north Tanzania's Arusha
Region.
</P>
<P>
The tourists, travelling in a truck, were forced to surrender
their cash, passports, video cameras, wrist watches and other
valuables after the bandits wielded sub-machine guns and stopped
them in a deep forest close to the Loroki Kimoi Village in the
Ngorongoro District, Sunday News said.
</P>
<P>
No one was hurt, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian police are combing the area and the anti-riot
Field Force Unit has arrived in the district to reinforce the
search for the bandits believed to be Somalis who crossed the
border into north Tanzania from Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Somali bandits are notorious for their acts in Arusha. Last
year, they shot dead a district police commander in the region.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Spanish tourists were travelling in a
truck belonging to a Kenyan safari company. It is suspected that
the gangsters tracked the tourists from Kenya and laid a trap in
the village. 
</P>
