<HEADLINE> Africa Can Learn from Uganda in HIV/AIDS Control: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) has said the HIV/AIDS epidemic can be overcome in Africa
judging by the success achieved in HIV/AIDS control programs in
Uganda, Zimbabwe's Sunday Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the WHO regional office for Africa in Harare, the
Ugandan experience "gives hope and relief that, at last, the
HIV/AIDS epidemic that is causing so much havoc, distress and
misery among families and communities on our continent can be
controlled and successfully kept in check and altogether avoided."
</P>
<P>
The regional office said a Ugandan report revealed that the
decline in HIV infection was particularly noticeable among young
persons of both sexes whose ages ranged from 15 to 19 years.
</P>
<P>
The decline was even more significant in teenage girls and
young women of between 15 and 19 years. For example, in 1992, 17
percent of sexually active teenage girls were found to be HIV
positive. This rate fell to seven percent in 1995 and currently
stood at six percent as at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan report indicated that similar declines had also
been recorded in persons attending clinics for the care of
sexually transmitted diseases (STD). In this group, nearly 50
percent were HIV positive in 1990.
</P>
<P>
However, only 29 percent of those seen at the clinics in 1998
were found to have HIV infection in combination with their other
STDs.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on this development in Harare last week, WHO
regional director for Africa Ebrahim Samba said, "The success
being achieved in Uganda should serve as an encouragement and
stimulus to all the national authorities on our continent to
intensify their commitment to and support for the HIV/AIDS
prevention and care programs which exist in every country under
the supervision and coordination of the national AIDS control
programs."
</P>
<P>
Samba said that a number of lessons could be learnt from the
success of the Uganda HIV/AIDS control program.
</P>
<P>
"The first lesson is that successful HIV/AIDS control programs
begin with national commitment at the highest level, with
openness, shared confidentiality and favorable laws and policies
to encourage people to be open about the disease, seek help and to
protect them from discrimination and victimization," said the WHO
official.
</P>
<P>
The second lesson is that aggressive and sustained HIV/AIDS
information and education programs paid dividends, Samba said.
</P>
<P>
"Information and education programs should be targeted at the
general public, high risk groups, but particularly at the young
people, in primary and secondary schools, street kids, farm hands
and all others," he added.
</P>
<P>
The third lesson is that HIV/AIDS prevention was and should be
the concern of all persons and all sectors of the society, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Above all," Samba noted, "the Ugandan experience demonstrates
that we can turn the tide against the HIV/AIDS scourge,
particularly among the young people, thereby making it possible
for us to save our future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
