<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S.Youth "Root Seeking Tour" Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- A ceremony to mark the beginning
of the '99 Chinese-American Youth "Root Seeking Tour" was held
here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 Chinese American kids from the state of
California of the United States will tour such historic cities as
Beijing, shanghai and Xi'an and participate in the activities of
cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
During their stay in Beijing, the kids will tour the Great Wall
and the Palace Museum, and attend the ceremony of raising the
Chinese national flag at the Tian'anmen Square in the heart of
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Root Seeking Tour is sponsored by the Overseas Chinese
Affairs Office of the State Council with the help of two U.S.
Chinese language schools to mark the 50th anniversary of the
founding of New China and the forthcoming Macao's return to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
The tour is also designed to improve the kids' understanding of
Chinese history, geography and culture, and their ability to use
Chinese language.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Weichao, deputy director of the State Council office,
said that this tour not only will help these kids to learn more
about their ancestors and today's China, but also will further the
mutual understanding between the people of China and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"Though you kids have learned something about your ancestors,
China is still unfamiliar to you," Zhang said, adding that "you'll
found that everyone here is your compatriot."
</P>
<P>
The leader of the tour Chiu ling said that traveling is as
helpful as reading, and she hoped the kids will find the national
sentiment, realize their responsibilities and find their roots
here through the tour.
</P>
<P>
Wu You and Huang Maoguo, the representatives of the kids, said
that they value this opportunity very much and will plant the root
of China into their hearts.
</P>
<P>
Xu Jialu, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, attended the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
