<HEADLINE> Foreign Firms Attracted by Lusaka Business Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- A one-million-U.S.-dollar project
to transform and extend the business district in Lusaka is to be
launched soon and several foreign engineering consultancy firms
are ready to carry out its feasibility studies.
</P>
<P>
The new Lusaka integrated development plan, which is aimed at
improving the physical, social, economical and institutional
welfare of Lusaka residents and attract investors, will be
financed by the World Bank through the zambian Ministry of Local
Government and Housing.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Sunday Mail newspaper quoted Director of the Lusaka
City Council Timothy Hakuyu as saying that the council's
projection for the next millennium was to transform and extend the
capital's central business district through a plot ration concept.
</P>
<P>
The program involves upgrading roads, land services, medical
facilities and housing. It will also help in attracting
investment and in the creation of more jobs.
</P>
<P>
It will cover a 10-year period with emphasis on the efficient
and equitable incorporation of existing settlement patterns into
the council's physical structure.
</P>
<P>
Hakuyu said the plan also encourages the expansion of the
district through construction of more multi-storey buildings.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Lusaka's master plan of structural development
has not been revised since 1978 due to financial limitations.
</P>
</TEXT>
