<HEADLINE> Venus Williams Topples Davenport at TIG Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- For one day, Lindsay Davenport
was second-best in California and to Venus Williams.
</P>
<P>
Williams temporarily put an end to Davenport's recent
dominance in her home state and stopped a personal five-match
losing streak against her with a 6-4, 7-5 victory in the
semifinals of the 520,000 U.S. dollars TIG Tennis Classic in San
Diego, California.
</P>
<P>
"It's annoying to keep losing to the same player over and over
again for no particular reason," Williams said. "I knew at some
point that had to change."
</P>
<P>
Davenport, the top seed and defending champion, suffered only
her second loss in her last 20 minutes in California, having swept
all three summer hardcourt events in her home state last year.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to take anything from how Williams played today,
" Davenport said. "I was a little off and she was better."
</P>
<P>
Seeded fourth, Williams will seek a WTA Tour-leading fifth
title of the year on Sunday. She will face the winner of Saturday'
s second semifinal between second seed Martina Hingis of
Switzerland and seventh seed Amanda Coetzer of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Less than a week after the two met in the final of the Bank of
the West Classic, Davenport and Williams engaged in an ugly battle
that featured a combined eight service breaks, five by Williams.
</P>
<P>
The reigning Wimbledon champion, Davenport fell to 35-6 this
season and lost for only the fourth time in 24 hardcourt matches
this season. She will try to win her second straight U.S. Open
later this summer.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, the 1997 champion, defeated Belgium's Dominique Van
Roost, 6-2, 6-4, on Thursday to secure a semifinal berth. Coetzer
advanced to the semifinals on Friday with a victory over unseeded
American Amy Frazier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
