<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan export dropped 28 percent to 839.8
million dollars in the first five months of this year as compared
with the same period of 1998 while its import fell 14.8 percent to
1.287 billion dollars, the Central Bank of Uruguay announced on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Export to the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) came down 37.8
percent to 389.9 million dollars from 626.8 million dollars while
imports from it dropped 17.7 percent, from 664.5 million dollars
to 547 million dollars. (Uruguay-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil confirmed Saturday that it will sue
Argentina before the World Trade Organization (WTO), after the
failure of the Mercosur foreign and economy ministers to settle
their trade disagreements.
</P>
<P>
"The talks will move now to the WTO," Brazilian Foreign
Minister Luiz Felipe Lampreia was quoted as saying. (Brazil-
Argentina-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran will be able to export more electric power to
neighboring Azerbaijan and Turkmenistan when its power line
installations complete by this yearend.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Energy Minister Habibollah Bitaraf said Friday that
power grid connections to the two countries through Ardabil
province in the west and Mazandaran province in the east are now
underway. (Iran-Power Export)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The Nigerian government is committed to prompt
completion of the on-going privatization so as to enable it to
concentrate efforts on other aspects of governance, Vice-President
Atiku Abubakar has said in capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The activities of government were usually slowed down when
distracted by issues meant for the private sector, Atiku said
Friday when addressing the House of Representative's Committee on
Privatization, The Guardian newspaper reported Saturday. (Nigeria-
Privatization)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- India's foreign currency assets rose by 168
million U.S. dollars to 30.760 billion dollars during the week
ended on July 30, the Reserve Bank of India said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the total foreign exchange reserves were up to 33.
474 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of March, the country's foreign currency assets
rose by 1.238 billion dollars. (India-Foreign Currency Assets)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- The tourists visiting the Maldives in the first
half of this year increased by 11.7 percent compared with the same
period last year, reports reaching here from Male said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During the period there were 216,351 tourists in comparison
with 193,712 during the corresponding period last year, the
reports said. (Sri Lanka-Maldives Tourists)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- A surge in the total profits of the half-time
score of Singapore's four major banks has proved that the country'
s banks have made a brisk recovery from the worst downturn the
city state has ever had.
</P>
<P>
With four of the five banking groups having reported their
interim 1999 results, their total profits of 1.36 billion
Singapore dollars (about 810 million U.S. dollars) have already
well exceeded the 1.2 billion Singapore dollars (about 714 million
U.S. dollars) the five largest banks made last year. (Singapore-
Banks) 
</P>
