<HEADLINE> Pan Am Games Enters Penultimate Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Pan Am top three
stepped up their gold-rush speed as the Winnipeg Games entered its
penultimate day here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The United States hauled in 10 golds, including a hat-trick
from the swimming pool, two from the water skiing and two from the
weightlifting.
</P>
<P>
Cuba, whose boxers bagged home four more titles Saturday,
landed 7 golds, third-placed host Canada following tightly with a
six-gold harvest.
</P>
<P>
The United States occupied the top spot in the medals count
with 101 golds, with Cuba and Canada second and third on 70 and 58
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Argentina placed the fourth with 25 and Brazil the fifth with
22.
</P>
<P>
Several competitions wrapped up their Winnipeg journey on
Saturday, including swimming, weightlifting, boxing, soccer and
softball.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian swimmers left the Pan Am pool on a high note as they
set a new Games record of 3:40.27 en route to the title of the men
's 4X100m medley relay, which concluded the Pan Am swimming
competitions.
</P>
<P>
Host Canada beat off the United States to emerge as the most
successful team from the Pan Am pool, with 13 golds, 5 silvers and
13 bronzes, its best record in the Pan Am history.
</P>
<P>
The American delegation, from which most of the first-choice
swimmers were absent to concentrate on the Pan Pacific swimming
championships later this month in Sydney, placed second with a 10-
18-4 record.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadorian strongman Boris Burov got his country off to the
gold medal count on the penultimate day of the 13th Pan Am Games,
winning the 105kg class title with a total lift of 397.5kg.
</P>
<P>
Cuba and the United States took a lion's share of the
weightlifting gold, each of them netting five, with Canada two and
Colombia, Ecuador and Dominica one respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the Pan Am boxing ring, Cuba was second to none. They
ruthlessly snared up 9 gold, with Argentina getting two and the
United States only one.
</P>
<P>
In the women's basketball final, Cuba outplayed the fiercely-
supported hosts Canada 72-63 to take the gold.
</P>
<P>
Mexico claimed gold in a weakly-fielded men's soccer tournament,
seeing off Honduras 3-1.
</P>
<P>
In the softball finals, Canada toughed out a 4-3 victory over
the United States for the men's gold while the American women took
a rapid revenge, nipping Canada 1-0 three hours later for the
title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
