<HEADLINE> Uruguayan Foreign Trade Down Sharply in First Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Uruguayan export dropped 28
percent to 839.8 million dollars in the first five months of this
year as compared with the same period of 1998 while its import
fell 14.8 percent to 1.287 billion dollars, the Central Bank of
Uruguay announced on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Export to the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) came down 37.8
percent to 389.9 million dollars from 626.8 million dollars while
imports from it dropped 17.7 percent, from 664.5 million dollars
to 547 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Trade with Brazil showed the sharpest decline, with export down
43.6 percent to 222.7 million dollars, and import down 23.1
percent to 244.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Though Brazil is still the biggest trade partner, export to it
made up 26.5 percent of Uruguay's export as against last year's 33.
8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Export to Argentina also dropped 29 percent to 143.1 million
dollars, and import was 296.6 million dollars, or 1.7 percent down.
</P>
