<HEADLINE> Deglau Takes Second Pan Am Gold in Record-breaking Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Jessica Deglau captured
her second Pan Am swimming title in style, trimming 0.13 seconds
off the 20-year-old Games record to lead a Canadian 1-2 finish in
the women's 200m butterfly here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Deglau, who won 200m freestyle four days ago, wrapped up the
course in 2:09.64 against the previous best mark of 2:09.77, which
was set by American Mary Meagher in the 1979 San Juan Games.
</P>
<P>
Her Canadian teammate Jennifer Button finished a well-beaten
second place in 2:12.09, with American Kalyn Keller third in 2:14.
60.
</P>
<P>
The women's 200m backstroke record also fell as the American
Denali Knapp blazed her way to gold in 2:12.48, eclipsing 0.5
seconds off the old mark.
</P>
<P>
1996 Olympic double gold medalist Beth Botsford had to settle
for the silver with her time of 2:12.95.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 200m individual medley, Canadian Allen Curtis
Myden touched in 2:02.38 to add another gold to her 400m medley
four days ago. American Joseph Montague was second in 2:03.08.
</P>
<P>
Montague's teammate Tammie Spatz broke the surfaces with a gold
in the women's 50m freestyle. Her winning time was 25.50 seconds,
well behind the world record set by Chinese Le Jingyi in Rome in
1994.
</P>
<P>
Men's 1500m freestyle gold was claimed by American T.V.
Siciliano, who clocked 15:14.94 to beat the field.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian swimmers left the Pan Am pool on a high note as they
set a new Games record of 3:40.27 en route to the title of the men
's 4X100m medley relay, which concluded the Pan Am swimming
competitions.
