<HEADLINE> Venezuela: No Evidence of Airliner Hijacked by Colombian Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Venezuelan government said
Saturday it has no concrete evidence to say that the Colombian
guerrillas hijacked the Venezuelan airliner that disappeared last
week.
</P>
<P>
The twin-motor Beechcraft light plane, owned by the Avior
Venezuelan airline with the YV 466 C license plate, lost contact
with the control tower when it was flying with 16 persons abroad
between the city of Barinas and the Guasdalito border community in
the southwest of Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan press reported that the Colombian army broadcast
on Friday night a dialogue between Jorge Briceno, chief of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), and his brother
German, which suggests the plane was diverted to that country.
</P>
<P>
It is presumed that the aircraft would be in the Colombian
department of Arauca near the border with Venezuela, and that the
passengers could have been taken Friday to a demilitarized jungle
zone in southeast of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Avior Vice President Jorge Anez said Friday in an interview
with the Venezuelan TV network, Globovision, that his firm will go
on searching for the plane and that he expects to have official
news in 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
An Avior aircraft was hijacked in 1998 on the same Barinas
route and used in clandestine flights by drug cartels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
