<HEADLINE> Brazil to Sue Argentina For Trade Restriction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Brazil confirmed Saturday that
it will sue Argentina before the World Trade Organization (WTO),
after the failure of the Mercosur foreign and economy ministers to
settle their trade disagreements.
</P>
<P>
"The talks will move now to the WTO," Brazilian Foreign
Minister Luiz Felipe Lampreia was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia returned Friday from Montevideo where he attended a
two-day emergency meeting of the foreign and economy ministers
from Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Common Market Council of Ministers members ended
the meeting without any concrete results, but agreed to let the
discrepancies to be discussed by the recently created Follow-up
Commission and the Macroeconomic Coordination Commission.
</P>
<P>
Trade relations between the countries have deteriorated since
January's devaluation of Brazil's currency.
</P>
<P>
To defend its industries against a flood of cheap imports,
Argentina recently slapped restrictions on several Brazilian goods,
and demanded that Brasilia indemnify its partners for the damage
caused by the devaluation of its currency.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Finance Minister Pedro Malan admitted that the
safeguard imposed by Argentina to the Brazilian textiles has a
legal base in the WTO agreements, but explained that Brazil does
not agree with the measure and also has legal bases to demand its
elimination.
</P>
<P>
These discrepancies among the Mercosur countries are considered
as the most serious since the creation of the regional trade
grouping. They weaken the main South American trade bloc when it
is preparing to negotiate free trade agreements with the European
Union (EU) and the other countries of America.
</P>
<P>
Trade within Mercosur countries reached 15 billion dollars in
1998. But Argentina's exports, almost all of which go to Brazil,
fell 27 percent in the first five months this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
