<HEADLINE> Menem Announces Measures to Support Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem announced Saturday a series of measures to support
agriculture and livestock industries.
</P>
<P>
The government will release 800 million pesos (800 million
dollars) in subsidy at an interest rate of 3 percent, Menem said
in an opening speech at the 113rd International Exhibition of
Agriculture and Livestock Industries.
</P>
<P>
Other measures also include the elimination of the tax on
diesel, a 25 percent cut in toll road payment for the transport of
agricultural products, and a 30 percent increase in tariff for
imported dairy products.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Argentine Nation will provide the supplying firms
with technological loans worth two billion pesos.
</P>
<P>
Other measures to be taken are the removal of the 5 percent
value added tax on pesticides, seeds and fertilizers, and a tax
cut on interest on the loans to small and medium enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Menem said Argentina had a record production of grains and oil-
bearing seeds in the 1997-98 harvest, or a 72 percent increase
over the last decade average, which was 39 million tons. 
