<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Logging Ban Stimulates China's Timber Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The logging ban since last year
in parts of China has prompted a big rise of timber imports to
China, but timber importers are now facing an oversupply on the
Chinese market and lower prices, the China Daily Business Weekly
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months of this year, five million cubic
meters of timer were imported, compared with 6 million cubic
meters last year. The amount of imports was a result of
overestimate of a projected timber shortage, the report quoted
Zhang Shiwei, deputy director of the National Timber Trade Market,
the biggest such market in China, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government implemented a logging ban in its
natural (non-cultured) forests last year in upper reaches of the
Yangtze and Yellow rivers. Many industry insiders predicted
domestic timber production would be reduced by 12-15 million cubic
meters or by one-fourth of the annual market supply.
</P>
<P>
They also expected market demand this year to continue to grow
as the nation works to stimulate the economy by investing heavily
in infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
However, the domestic production of timber for commercial uses
has only dropped by about 2 million cubic meters, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
That was because forests in northeastern forests, which
account for the biggest share of market supply, can still be
logged. And to avoid a timber shortage, the government has reduced
tariffs on timber imports and has cut wood product tariffs to zero.
It allowed many more firms to import timber than before the
logging ban.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, imports of timber have soared and imported
timber varieties have also multiplied. Imports came mainly from
southeast Asia, Russia, Europe, Africa and the south Pacific.
</P>
<P>
As stockpiles grow, timber buyers are getting picky and the
prices of timber are sliding. On average, prices have fallen by 5
percent to 10 percent, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Prices of precious timber varieties, whose use and sales are
limited, in particular, have plunged by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Timber imports will mainly focus on precious varieties and
those with large diameters," said Kou Wenzheng, director general
of the forestry resources administration department of the State
Forestry Administration.
</P>
<P>
He said domestic demand will be met mainly by relying on
cultured forests, by increasing timber-use efficiency and by
developing wood supplements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greene and Jones Shine in British Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Greene clocked 9.97 seconds, ahead of Bruny Surin's 10.02, to
become the first man to break the 10 second barrier in the British
soil.
</P>
<P>
Briton Dwain Chambers was third in 10.04 but Olympic champion
Donovan Bailey struggled home in last place.
</P>
<P>
Jones roared to 10.80 to become first woman inside 11 seconds
in Britain. Ukrainian Zhanna Pintusevich followed her home in 10.
98 to become the second. The previous best of 11.02 was set by
Merlene Ottey 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Haile Gebrselassie, the little Ethiopian with 15 world records
to his name, posted eight minutes 1.72 seconds to fall short of
Daniel Komen's 7:58.61 two mile world best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
