<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Mission in E. Timor Might Pull Out if Security Worsens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The UN Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) might pull out if security conditions deteriorate in the
run-up to the autonomy ballot scheduled for August 30, its leader
said Saturday in Dili, capital of East Timor, reports reaching
here Sunday from Dili said.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas,
UNAMET Chief Ian Martin said further talks to coordinate security
measures in the tense region would be held next week in Jakarta,
capita of Indonesia, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, Indonesia, and Portugal -- East Timor's
former colonial ruler -- will take part in the talks, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
"I told Alatas that if... East Timor is in a dangerous
situation, then the UN mission will have a plan to evacuate its
staff," Martin said.
</P>
<P>
The warning came a day after voter registration for the ballot
in most areas in East Timor ended. UN officials said voter rolls
could top 450,000, exceeding their most optimistic projections.
</P>
<P>
The plebiscite will allow East Timor's 800,000 inhabitants to
choose whether they want to become a self-governing entity within
Indonesia. If the proposal is rejected, Indonesia has said, it
would grant full independence to East Timor which was integrated
into Indonesia in 1976 and become the country's 27th province.
</P>
<P>
However, sporadic violence colored the run-up to the ballot
with the last incident revealed on Friday by UNAMET spokesman
Yusuhiro Ueki. He said a UNAMET official was slightly wounded by a
chunk of concrete when some 20 pro-integration militias attacked a
house in Ainaro regency on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday at 2:30 p.m. a registration post at the state
Batugade high school was attacked by at least 50 militiamen. Two
other registration posts in the vicinity immediately closed.
</P>
<P>
Alatas, who was accompanied by six ministers including Defense
Minister Wiranto and Coordinating Minister for Political and
Security Affairs Feisal Tanjung, arrived in Dili Saturday for a
one-day visit to discuss various issues on the autonomy ballot.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said Saturday in Dili that the presence of the UNAMET to
help conduct a poll on the territory's political future did not
mean Indonesia's diplomacy in international fora had become
stagnant.
</P>
<P>
In fact, he said, Indonesia had been trying to find a solution
to the question of East Timor since 1983 through dialogue with
Portugal under the supervision of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Alatas expressed the hope that there would be no further delays
in the direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
The vote on whether the people of East Timor will remain part
of Indonesia with wide-ranging autonomy or be a separate state was
originally scheduled for August 8 but was later delayed for two
weeks following a spate of violence and attacks on UNAMET
personnel. Lastly it was delayed again until August 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pastrana: Inte'l Commission Indispensable for Colombia Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Andres Pastrana said Saturday it was indispensable to create an
international verification commission to monitor the talks between
the Colombian government and the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia (FARC), the biggest guerrilla group in the country.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks at the ceremony commemorating
the 180th anniversary of the Boyaca Battle, a symbol of freedom of
the nation.
</P>
<P>
He said that peace without guaranties was no peace at all and
that negotiations without them were only a sterile and
irresponsible exercise.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana insisted that only when such a verifying mechanism is
established should the government and the FARC be able to start
the negotiation process that has been postponed on two occasions,
which has caused much concern to the Colombians.
</P>
<P>
High Commissioner for Peace Victor G. Ricardo and Raul Reyes,
one of the FARC spokesmen, will hold a two-day meeting starting
next Monday in San Vicente del Caguan to elaborate the creation of
the commission.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana, who completed one year of his mandate on the same day,
reviewed in his speech in homage to the heroes who died in
fightings his efforts made against all adversities in seeking
peace in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope in achieving peace in his country though he
admitted "the road to peace" is strewn with thorns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
