<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Argentines Visiting Malvinas Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The first group of
Argentines, most of them journalists, left Saturday for the
Malvinas Islands after travel by Argentines to the islands was
permitted last month.
</P>
<P>
The group left the Chilean capital of Santiago aboard Chilean
airline Lanchile Flight 991 and will arrive at Mount Pleasant
airport in the Malvinas within several hours, reports reaching
here said.
</P>
<P>
The flight was the first after the Chilean government agreed to
resume flights from the continent to the disputed archipelago,
which had been suspended since last March by Chile in retaliation
for the detention of its lifetime Senator Augusto Pinochet in
London. Chile is the only South American country which agrees to
open flights to the Malvinas.
</P>
<P>
Argentine Foreign minister Guido di Tella and his British
counterpart, Robin Cook, signed an agreement on July 14 permitting
Argentines to travel to those islands, for which the two countries
fought a war in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Argentines were permitted to travel to the islands only on
humanity grounds, such as relatives of soldiers killed in the war
and those with double nationality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
