<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Produces Over 48,000 Tons of Sugar in 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar produced a total of 48,398
tons of sugar in fiscal 1998-99, which ended in March, according
to the latest Economic Indicators published by the country's
Central Statistical Organization.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar cultivates over 100,000 hectares of sugarcane with an
annual output of over 5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Sugar production of the country remained steady for the past
three years, maintaining at over 50,000 tons annually.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Ministry of Agriculture and Irrigation has adopted
some measures to increase sugar production by disbursing loan and
granting advanced payment to sugarcane growers.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the Myanmar government has
been allowing the private sector to reclaim vacant, virgin, fallow
and wet lands for cultivation of industrial raw material crops
including sugarcane, jute, cotton, tobacco and coffee.
</P>
<P>
There are 10 more sugar mills being built by the state-run
Myanmar Sugarcane Enterprise in recent years in the areas of
Paukkaung, Pyay and Aunglan in Bago and Magway divisions where
there are enough sugarcane resources.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar exports over 35,000
tons of sugar annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Economy Grows 8.4 Percent In First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Tibet Autonomous
Region enjoyed a GDP of 3.85 billion yuan during the first half of
this year, up 8.4 percent over the same period last year,
according to the region's official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The regional statistics bureau said that Tibet had an
industrial output value of 540 million yuan during the six months,
an increase of 14.9 percent. The state industrial sector suffered
a net loss of 1.13 million yuan, but this figure was down by 43.9
million yuan from the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that although the scale of Tibet's economy is
rather small compared with other provinces and autonomous regions,
its rate of growth is rather laudable.
</P>
<P>
The regions' posts and telecommunications saw its business rise
by 14 percent and 57 percent respectively, exports shot up by 38
percent, and the region attracted 32 percent more tourists, some
89,000 people from home and abroad, than in the first half last
year.
</P>
<P>
Tibet's retail sales volume rose by 4.8 percent on an annual
basis to two billion yuan during the first half.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
