<HEADLINE> Japan Offers to Clean U.S.-Contaminated Firing Ranges in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
shown interest in cleaning the contaminated areas used by the
United States in Panama as firing ranges.
</P>
<P>
Japanese ambassador Yasuyuki Fujishima was quoted Saturday by
Panamanian press as saying that his government is willing to
cooperate in the studies to determine the contamination levels in
those areas.
</P>
<P>
Fujishima said that if Panama and the United States could reach
an agreement on a possible Japanese participation in those studies,
Japan is ready to collaborate.
</P>
<P>
But the Japanese embassy has not received any formal notes, he
said, adding if the Panamanian government acts on it, Japan will
set to work immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Torrijos-Carter treaties signed in 1977 by then U.S.
President Jimmy Carter and the late chief of the Panamanian
government Omar Torrijos, state that Panama must receive the areas
used by the U.S. army duly cleansed of contaminants. 
</P>
