<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Reports Steady Export Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The effort to increase exports in
north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region is yielding results,
with exports rising 11 percent to 420 million U.S. dollars during
the first six months of this year, according to local official
sources.
</P>
<P>
Much of the increase came from increased barter trade, which
was up nearly 50 percent to 180 million U.S. dollars during the
period, trade officials said.
</P>
<P>
The region's foreign trade turnover was 665 million U.S.
dollars, a year-on-year increase of over 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
To give a lift to exports, the regional government has offered
tax rebates to exporters, given private enterprises export
licenses, and encouraged more enterprises to engage in border
trade.
</P>
<P>
Export controls have also been decentralized for greater
efficiency, and pillar industries, whose exports account for
almost half the region's total, have been given priority by the
regional government.
</P>
<P>
A strategy to tap into new markets was also adopted, and
exports to new markets in North America grew as much as 56 percent,
and those to Latin America by 88 percent during the January-June
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
