<HEADLINE> Animal Husbandry Flourishes in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Livestock raising is flourishing
in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, as a total of
26.1 million head of livestock have been raised this year, an
increase of 1.09 million over 1998.
</P>
<P>
Regional officials said this record output was a hard-won
success, given the damage to pasture land and the spreading of
epidemic diseases among the livestock as a result of last year's
catastrophic flooding.
</P>
<P>
This sector received a strong boost when the regional
government adopted the strategy of focusing on raising
thoroughbred animals, which now account for more than 70 percent
of the total.
</P>
<P>
Improving infrastructure in the grassland also laid a solid
foundation for developing animal husbandry, and usable grassland
for livestock farming is nearing ten million hectares at present,
and continues to increase at an annual rate of two million
hectares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
