<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Next Pan Am Games to Be Slimmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The 14th Pan Am Games,
which will take place in four years in Santo Domingo, the
Dominican Republic, will be slimmer.
</P>
<P>
"We have to do some of reduction. We have to reduce the amount
of sports, " Jose Joaquin Puello, president of the Santo Domingo
Games Organization Committee said at a news conference Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He made sure that every sport that has been included in the
Summer Olympics will be staged in Santo Domingo.
</P>
<P>
"But we're also considering some of the most popular sports in
the South America," he said."The total will be no more than 28-30
sports."
</P>
<P>
But the final word belonged to the Pan American Sports
Organization (PASO), the governing body of the American regional
sports.
</P>
<P>
The organization committee are enthusiastic that the official
responsibility of hosting the next Pan Am Games will be handed to
them in Sunday night's closing ceremonies, Puello said. But it's
also a "great challenge of the new millennium, because we are a
small country".
</P>
<P>
The "excellent athletes village" and "excellent sports venues",
however, will be for sure, Puello promised, saying the budget of
the Games will be 105 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
And there will be no problem in lodging, because the country
is a well-known tourism paradise, he said.
</P>
<P>
As the Winnipeg Games approaches its finale, the Pan Am Games
officials began to do a little bit of soul searching to look at
both sides of what had been called as "the best ever organized
Games" by the PASO president Mario Vazquez Rana.
</P>
<P>
Some suggest the Games are too big, too long and they might be
too expensive.
</P>
<P>
And that's also exactly what the president of the 13th Pan Am
Games, Don MacKenzie says he's going to recommend.
</P>
<P>
"When we meet in Mexico City on September 16 for our
debriefing, I'm going to recommend that the size of the Games be
reduced from 42 sports to maybe 28 or 30," said the man who
brought the 13th Games to Winnipeg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
