<DOCNO> XIE19990808.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Sports Make Big Strides at Pan Am Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four years ago, weightlifter Wanda Rijo would not have been in
the Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
Not because she wasn't strong enough, or talented enough, but
because she's a woman, and women's weightlifting was the
equivalent of men's synchronized swimming -- it didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
Last night, Rijo lifted 220 kilograms of steel above her head,
alongside the men who have been doing it for years, to award the
Dominican Republic its first gold in the Games.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1995 Pan Am Games in Argentina, women's participation
in the Games has skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
In Mar Del Plata, only 29 women's teams were entered, compared
with 68 men's team.
</P>
<P>
This year, 47 women's teams competed, while the men's
contingent has only grown by one team -- the roller hockey event.
</P>
<P>
On any given day at these Games, spectators have been able to
watch women competing in tough sports such as water polo, team
handball and basketball.
</P>
<P>
But fans also enjoyed more stereo typically feminine pursuits
such as synchronized swimming and rhythmic gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, the fans have been watching in droves.
</P>
<P>
The women's softball tournament has attracted more fans than
the men's tournament and crowds for women's water polo were equal
to those watching the men compete.
</P>
<P>
Women's volleyball, basketball and team handball have also been
big draws.
</P>
<P>
Softball made its Olympic debut to great fanfare in Atlanta and
next year, women will compete, along with the men, in water polo
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
But popular culture still has a hard time recognizing women as
serious athletes.
</P>
<P>
Strong, aggressive women are considered "unfeminine" in some
cultures.
</P>
<P>
But at least, as far as the 13th Pan Am Games are concerned,
the situation is improving. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
