<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Develop Gigantic Grape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Grape experts in east China's
Zhejiang Province have developed a kind of grape as large as a
table-tennis ball.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Wenbin, head of the Wujiang Grape Research Institute in
Jinhua City of Zhejiang Province, claimed that each grape weighs
between 22 g and 25 g on average and a bunch of them weighs over 2.
5 kg.
</P>
<P>
He said the new variety of grape was developed from a kind of
grape introduced from Japan to northeast China's Liaoning Province
by grafting a dozen times over the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Jiang Wenbin applied to the Guinness Book of Records
Office in Shanghai to register a grape that he had grown as the
biggest in the world. The grape weighed 36 g and its diameter was
3.85 cm. His claim was recognized later.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
