<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Italians on Summer Vacation, Survey Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 7 (Xinhua) -- As the peak of the holiday season
approaches, a survey has found that fewer Italians are going on
vacation this summer, and many have still not made up their minds.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out by the Italian national hotel
association Federalberghi, found that 23 million Italians will be
staying at home this year compared to 20 million last summer.
</P>
<P>
It said 6 percent are still undecided, in spite of the upcoming
August 15 national holiday, when many Italian cities will grind to
a virtual halt.
</P>
<P>
Milan will be one of the most deserted spots during the holiday
weekend, with only 38 percent of inhabitants opting to stay home,
according to the newspaper of Osservatorio di Milano.
</P>
<P>
However, tight finances, especially in the south, will keep
more than 58 percent of city dwellers at home across the country.
</P>
<P>
Federalberghi's president, Alberto Sangregorio, said the latest
figures were worrying, and noted that the summer had also seen a
drop in the number of German tourists, Italy's largest group of
foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
According to the Osservatorio di Milano, fewer Italians are
taking traditional month - long summer holidays and many more are
opting instead to take a 10-day break some time between June and
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
