<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Vows to Hunt Down Embassy Bombers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States vowed on
Saturday at the anniversary of its embassy bombings that it would
continue to hunt down and capture the masterminds behind the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
"Today we vow that America will not be intimidated. We will not
retreat from the world. We will not rest until every one of those
responsible for the embassy bombings has been brought to justice,"
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said at a gathering that
marked the the anniversary of the bombings.
</P>
<P>
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania were blown up by car bombs
on August 7, 1998, killing 226 people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read by National Security Adviser Sandy Berger
at the ceremony, President Bill Clinton said the victims
represented "everything that is right about our country and the
world."
</P>
<P>
The State Department recently warned all 265 embassies and
consulates around the world to pay particular attention to
security in the run-up to the anniversary out of fear of possible
copycat strikes, and warned all citizens worldwide to stay
vigilant about their personal security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
