<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces 120 Million Dollars in Education Grants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday announced 120 million U.S. dollars in grants intended to
put higher education within young people's reach.
</P>
<P>
"Now is not the time to turn our backs on our children's
future," Clinton said in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
"As far as we've come, we know, still, there is much to do --
for too many children, especially in economically distressed
communities, aren't getting the chance to reach their highest
potential," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he will ask the Republican-controlled Congress to
double the financial commitment to the program "so that we can
reach more of our children than ever."
</P>
<P>
He said he wants to build on current efforts to encourage
national teaching standards and to increase scholarship funds for
tuition tax credits.
</P>
<P>
Because of these efforts, Clinton said, more young people have
the chance to make the most of their abilities and take their
places in the high-tech world of the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
